statement:
Suppose that the matrix \emph{A} has the following singular value
decomposition:

\begin{align*}A = \begin{bmatrix}
0 & 1 \\ 1 & 0
\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}
\sigma_1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & \sigma_2 & 0
\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}
1/\sqrt 2 & 1/\sqrt 2 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \\ -1\sqrt 2 & 1/\sqrt 2 & 0
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

where $\sigma_1 \geq \sigma_2 \geq 0$.

\textbf{(b)} Write down an orthonormal basis for \emph{N(A)} and an
orthonormal basis for \emph{R(A)}.

sols:
The equation for the singular value matrix decomposition is

$A$ = $U \Sigma V^*$ = $U \Sigma V^T$

$=
\begin{bmatrix}
0&1\\1&0
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
\sigma_1&0 &0
\\0 & \sigma_2 & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{1}{\sqrt(2)} & 0 & -\frac{1}{\sqrt(2)}
\\ \frac{1}{\sqrt(2)} & 0 & \frac{1}{\sqrt(2)}
\\ 0 & 1 & 0
\end{bmatrix}$

It can be seen that the third column of V is an orthogonal basis for
N(A), and both columns of U form the basis for R(A).
